WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African-American History and Culture.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:20.000
Today is Wednesday, June 8, 2011. My name is Joe Manier of the Southern Oral History Program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:28.000
I'm with the videographer John Bishop and we are in Columbia, South Carolina at the home of Justice Ernest Vinny Jr.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:43.000
and we are here to do an oral history interview for the Civil Rights History Project which is a joint undertaking of the Smithsonian's National Museum of African-American History and Culture and the Library of Congress.

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:51.000
Justice Vinny, thank you so much for sitting down with us and welcoming us to your home and this is Vinny as well and it's a real honor and privilege to be with you.

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:55.000
Thank you. I'm delighted to be here. She had this moment with you.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:01:05.000
Good bye, Koo. Let me take you back to begin our conversation with some reflection perhaps on your father and your aunts and you're growing up.

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:23.000
Well, my father was a school teacher primarily and my aunts shed the responsibility of rearing me since my mother had died when I was ten days old.

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:30.000
So it was a conglomeration between my father and my aunts primarily.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:33.000
Can you say a little more about your father?

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:50.000
Well, he was an educator, a graduate of Virginia State University, Virginia State College and he was teaching in Smithfield, Virginia.

00:01:50.000 --> 00:02:00.000
And I was born in Smithfield and he was a strict constructionist, I'd say, if he were a lawyer.

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:08.000
But he ruled the Roost in a fan impassure manner.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:16.000
As long as I understood that he was the boss and I was to do what I was told to do when I was told to do it.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:23.000
But other than that, we traveled from one end of Virginia to another.

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:37.000
I don't know how many elementary schools I went to because all he had to do was get an offer of a better job and we'd have our backs packed within 24 hours and be on our own.

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:43.000
That's about how we got to South Carolina.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:56.000
He had been teaching school in Virginia all of his life and when World War II began, he decided that he would go to Washington and work in the Pentagon.

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:10.000
After a year or two there, he decided that he wanted to go back to teaching and he went to Baltimore where he taught at Morgan State University.

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:25.000
And while at Morgan State University, according to the stirs they told me he got a call from Claflin College in Orangeburg and they offered him a job in Orangeburg as Dean of Claflin.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:32.000
And lo and behold, the next thing I knew I was on a train headed to South Carolina.

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:49.000
A place I had never been to had no idea the only thing I knew about it was the stories out here and the stories were told by my young friends who advised me that I was going to a place where they were probably going to end up lynching me.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:04:03.000
But I thought they were telling the truth. When we got into Florence, the PD River, as I recall, was on one of its high levels.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:14.000
And I said, oh my God, the conductor said, Florence is the next stop and you're changing Florence for Orangeburg.

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:23.000
I knew that this Orangeburg place was a place full of water and alligators and various and sundry other things.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:30.000
But lo and behold, when I stepped off the train in Orangeburg, they were human beings, they were nice people.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:35.000
And once I got to know them, they treated us as family.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:43.000
And all the stories that my young friends had lied to me about were exaggerated.

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:46.000
So, where did you come down to Clapwell?

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:58.000
I think it was 1946 or 45. I was a junior or something like that in high school.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:08.000
Other impressions, you just said that the welcome you received by the community in Orangeburg and around Clapwell was a warm one.

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:14.000
Can you talk a little bit more about your impressions of the town, of the college?

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:23.000
Well, this was my first day and I was scared out of my wit scene. I was in a strange town, didn't know anybody, nobody knew me.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:33.000
I didn't know what it was going to be like. But it proved to be a welcome that I was pleased with.

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:40.000
And within a year or so after I had arrived in Orangeburg, I had a job.

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:45.000
I went to work at the college soda shop as a soda jerk.

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:57.000
And that was an interesting experience because the college soda shop was located right on the perimeters of two colleges.

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:06.000
And that was where the young people hung out and drank sodas and ate hamburgers and enjoyed life.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:13.000
And the people were warm and friendly. The family that owned the soda shop was the Weber family.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:22.000
And the Weber's were instrumental in the business community. And they treated me as if I was a member of the family.

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:27.000
And I think I worked there for about six, eight years, something longer than that.

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:30.000
What was the African American family or what family?

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:35.000
African American family. How vibrant was the African American business community?

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:45.000
Well, I was very young. So I don't have any independent recollection of the high vibrant business community was.

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:55.000
But it was an active community. It was a community that was actively involved in the events of the total community.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:07:03.000
One of the things I do recall doing my stay at Claflin, either the first or second years somewhere along in there,

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:11.000
the Ku Klux Klan perparated down the street right in front of Claflin and South Carolina State.

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:19.000
It was an interesting spectacle.

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:23.000
Were you and your father members of the church community?

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:34.000
Yes, we were. We were members of the Trinity United Methodist Church, which is located still right across the street from Claflin and State College.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:37.000
So you enrolled in 48 as an undergraduate at Claflin?

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:39.000
Something like that.

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:46.000
What was your sense of what you hoped to do and be at that point as you could recall?

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:52.000
Well, at that time I had not formalized what my ambition was going to be.

00:07:52.000 --> 00:08:05.000
I think I probably formally set my goals after we left Claflin and went to Morgan State.

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:17.000
I got an opportunity to observe these positions of black lawyers and how they were treated in the black community in Washington.

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:19.000
It was interesting.

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:27.000
So after your stay, after your studies at Claflin, you went back to DC?

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:31.000
No, no, I did not go back to DC.

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:35.000
But earlier, I had a few lawyers at Claflin.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:38.000
So you had that sense of that gave you some sense that that might be a path?

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:43.000
That might be who I wanted to hook my style.

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:49.000
Oh yes, I worked in DC before.

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:56.000
I came to the Orangeburg. I worked in a shoe store.

00:08:56.000 --> 00:09:08.000
Can you tell me a little bit more about how you came to observe black attorneys in DC in those years?

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:16.000
Well, my family was always reading and doing something.

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:27.000
And I remember there was a lawyer in Washington named Belford V. Lawson, who was president of a fraternity, who was a national leader.

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:32.000
He was dressed always immaculately.

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:39.000
How I remember.

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:46.000
You entered in the fall of 52. You began your law studies at the college in Orangeburg, College of Law.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:50.000
And the many parts of that experience that I'm interested in asking about.

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:58.000
Can you recall your sense of your fellow students and the faculty in the facility?

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:03.000
Well, the faculty was dedicated, hard working.

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:07.000
Sometimes you'd go to class, we didn't have, but about four students in the class.

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:12.000
Sometimes you'd go to class, wouldn't about to be the but you, the teacher.

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:15.000
And so you got individual attention.

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:26.000
And they did not play. They worked hard because I gathered from my recollection of that period of time.

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:45.000
The students and the faculty were out and about trying to make sure that South Carolina State's law school was able to produce the caliber of lawyers, which would justify its existence and make it a part of the history of Carolina.

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:50.000
And I think they succeeded very well.

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:57.000
One question I had was, do you happen to recall, I should have checked this before the interview, but I did not.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:04.000
Do you recall what year the University of South Carolina Law School was finally desegregated?

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:06.000
I do not.

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:11.000
But it had not been desegregated and would not have been, I imagine, until maybe the mid-50s.

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:31.000
Somewhere along in there, because as I recall it correctly, one of the people responsible for the desegregation at the University of South Carolina was a student who was enrolled at the University of South Carolina State named John W. Wrighten.

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:44.000
And as a result of his activities, and I think he instituted a lawsuit which resulted in the desegregation of the University of South Carolina.

00:11:44.000 --> 00:12:00.000
On graduating and taking the bar, that would have been early summer 1954, which was just then weeks after the Brown decision.

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:02.000
That's correct.

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:08.000
Do you happen to recall your reaction to Brown and its discussion on the campus and things?

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:15.000
Well, as I recall it, the reaction was aesthetic.

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:27.000
There was what we had wanted and what we had hoped for and what we hoped the Supreme Court would do in its decision.

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:46.000
And of course, there was some trepidation because we did not know what the implementing decision was going to be and it ended up being longer, taking longer than we had hoped.

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:53.000
Yes, we do.

00:12:53.000 --> 00:13:04.000
Can you talk about what challenges faced a young African-American attorney in the mid-50s trying to begin a career in a life in South Carolina?

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:19.000
Well, it was strange because by and large there had been very few lawyers in South Carolina at the time I became a lawyer.

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:26.000
And it was a new experience for the black community as you would talk with them.

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:43.000
They didn't understand that if you were a black lawyer you could go into the courthouse and pull the books down and do the things that a lawyer would normally do in order to perform his services for clientele.

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:50.000
So, sometimes you take them to the courthouse just to show them you would walk in the front door of the courthouse.

00:13:50.000 --> 00:14:06.000
And you would continually try to encourage them to get their students, their friends to submit their cases to you.

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:21.000
And I think one of the things that was most disappointing to me as an individual was the fact that there was with the establishment of the law school at South Carolina State,

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:28.000
the establishment of a law school at North Carolina Central.

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:37.000
And these two schools in our view were similar.

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:48.000
But eventually South Carolina decided that in the exercise of its judgment that it was closed the law school at the South Carolina State.

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:53.000
And we had often wondered why?

00:14:53.000 --> 00:15:02.000
Because as my information now tells me that North Carolina Central has somewhere around 300 students,

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:10.000
it's a fully integrated and a full part of the legal education program of North Carolina,

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:16.000
where South Carolina State's law school has become a closed entity.

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:30.000
And to my perspective, it could have benefited, the state could have benefited if they had maintained that and that's one of the disappointments we have in our life.

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:34.000
Sure. I live in Chapel Hill just down the road from Durham.

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:41.000
So my sense of the history of Central's law school is just as you've described it.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:49.000
And its history was almost equivalent to South Carolina State.

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:58.000
They were very similar, they created and very similar in their structure.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:04.000
In fact, many of the faculty members from South Carolina State, when it closed up,

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:10.000
that's law school, went to North Carolina.

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:14.000
In the through the 50s, you taught school in Conway.

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:22.000
No, not through the 50s, I think, for about six years, early. Yes, I did.

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:25.000
What was that experience?

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:28.000
Well, I was a son of a teacher.

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:34.000
And so I had an appreciation of the significance of education.

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:39.000
And it was an interesting and challenging experience.

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:49.000
And it provided me with insights into the problems and dilemmas with which my student body was confronted.

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:55.000
Not only did I teach school, but in the evenings I worked with Dan in Conway.

00:16:55.000 --> 00:17:02.000
And I picked up a job of two working at a hotel, then.

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:17.000
I know that there's a story sometimes recounted about your experience at a hotel in relation to the annual meeting in South Carolina.

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:22.000
That's a true story.

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:26.000
I was working at the Ocean Forest Hotel.

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:35.000
And when the bar association had its meeting down there, I think it was in 1954, 55.

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:40.000
Blacks were not invited to attend the social events.

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:49.000
Though we were members of the bar, we could go to the educational seminars and things like that.

00:17:49.000 --> 00:18:01.000
But my first meeting at a South Carolina bar association, I went as a waiter at the Ocean Forest Hotel.

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:08.000
And somehow another of the words got out and later on in my career, when I became Chief Justice,

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:14.000
I used to tell the story that my first meeting at the bar was as a waiter.

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:23.000
But sooner or later I had acquired sufficient influence or connections or whatever you want to call it,

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:31.000
that I was at the head table at a future meeting of the South Carolina bar, which demonstrated,

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:39.000
to some extent, the progress we were making in certain aspects of the culture in South Carolina.

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:51.000
When did you, I know in 1960, you're going to move to Sumter and become very directly engaged in as an attorney and representing Civil Rights Planets.

00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:56.000
But through that second half of the 50s, while you were teaching in Conway,

00:18:56.000 --> 00:19:03.000
did you have much engagement with the network of black attorneys who were litigating those early civil rights cases?

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:12.000
Well, we did have a close connection between the entire black legal community in South Carolina.

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:20.000
And to the extent possible, with my limited capacity to be actively involved,

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:25.000
I did keep abreast and kept me informed.

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:41.000
In fact, it was as a result of a mission where Matthew Perry and I.D. Newman came through some of the things

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:52.000
that were something that they were on their way to somewhere about the opening of a state park.

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:56.000
And that stimulated certain juices to flow.

00:19:56.000 --> 00:20:04.000
And as a result, I made a decision that I was going to take my wife and two children,

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:12.000
and no one child, and leave Sumter and become a full-time fraction.

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:14.000
I love you.

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:24.000
Now, when I say full-time, I was reluctant to give up a full-time gig.

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:37.000
When I went to Sumter, one of the first people that communicated with me was the President of Morris College, Dr. O'Rouven.

00:20:37.000 --> 00:20:48.000
And I was going to move and excuse me, was any thing that he thought that I could do.

00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:58.000
And blowing the whole, he offered me a job teaching at the Marsh College in South Carolina history,

00:20:58.000 --> 00:21:06.000
which was right down my... I'm not even one class a week, two or three days a week.

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:13.000
And so that aided in my transition from...

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:15.000
Sure.

00:21:15.000 --> 00:21:17.000
Towards Sumter and then.

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:18.000
Thank you, towards Sumter.

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:23.000
You mentioned Reverend Newman, and I believe in those years he was...

00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:29.000
Field Secretary of the NAACP, yes.

00:21:29.000 --> 00:21:31.000
Can you tell me some recollections about Reverend Newman?

00:21:31.000 --> 00:21:35.000
I'd like to have a description of him in the record.

00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:40.000
As I recall it, I'm getting older by the day.

00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:51.000
But as I recall, it Reverend Newman was actively involved in whatever Chief Counsel Perry was involved in,

00:21:51.000 --> 00:21:59.000
in the desegregation of the State Park that they were working on.

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:09.000
And Reverend Newman was actively involved in everything that was going on on the civil rights community at that time.

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:15.000
Obviously, in the...

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:18.000
We're going to switch tracks here for a moment.

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:33.000
Just that explosion of protest in early 1960 and how you then stepped forward to represent so many of the young people and others who were taking roles in direct action protests.

00:22:34.000 --> 00:22:36.000
Ask you a question. I'll try to answer it.

00:22:36.000 --> 00:22:41.000
Tell me about your recollections of the Friendship Nine.

00:22:41.000 --> 00:22:47.000
Well, the Friendship Nine was a bit later on in the history.

00:22:47.000 --> 00:23:02.000
The Friendship Nine, I got a call from Brock Hill, and somebody said that there are some students connected with Friendship College that are about to do something that could cause them to be arrested.

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:05.000
And would I represent them?

00:23:05.000 --> 00:23:11.000
And of course, I said, yes, I'd be pleased to represent them.

00:23:11.000 --> 00:23:18.000
And they were connected with the Congress of Racial Equalities, I remember it.

00:23:18.000 --> 00:23:30.000
And the Congress of Racial Equalities, field secretary, was a gentleman by the name of James T. McCain, who was very active.

00:23:30.000 --> 00:23:35.000
And guess what? He was the citizen of Sopta.

00:23:35.000 --> 00:23:46.000
So I knew him, and after receiving a call from the Racial community, I decided I'd go.

00:23:46.000 --> 00:23:55.000
And the first time I got called to the Racial, I never will forget it.

00:23:56.000 --> 00:24:09.000
My old ragged a car broke down. And there was a story written up in the paper which says that the Friendship Nine's lawyer was unable to get to court, and it had to be postponed.

00:24:09.000 --> 00:24:18.000
Well, that was not as newsworthy. I don't know what they were doing yet, but I got to Rock Hill eventually.

00:24:18.000 --> 00:24:28.000
And I got to meet these 10 or 12 students. And it was a simple demonstration.

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:36.000
As far as I knew, these nine people were going to be tried and get convicted.

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:42.000
And I would have gotten a bond, and they would have been out.

00:24:42.000 --> 00:24:52.000
Well, somewhere, somebody had not fully informed their lawyer as to what they were going to up about it.

00:24:52.000 --> 00:25:11.000
And, Lauren Behold, after we had tried it, and the judge had imposed his sentence, they then announced to me that they had a new facet of the Civil Rights Movement.

00:25:11.000 --> 00:25:18.000
They were going to do their jail time and not put up a bar.

00:25:18.000 --> 00:25:21.000
That was the first I knew about that.

00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:36.000
Because in these days, the lawyers had to walk a fine line between what they could tell their clients and what the clients would tell them.

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:45.000
The first time I found out about jail without bail was after the conviction, as I recall it.

00:25:45.000 --> 00:25:48.000
I knew I was shocked.

00:25:48.000 --> 00:26:01.000
And I was shocked for a number of reasons. There was another organization involved in that Rock Hill community called SNCC, Student Non-Balance Association.

00:26:01.000 --> 00:26:18.000
I didn't know who was calling the shots for the students, but I knew I wasn't and wouldn't go let myself get boxed into instituting some lawsuit or being available or participating in that.

00:26:18.000 --> 00:26:25.000
But they were ready to do what they were going to do.

00:26:25.000 --> 00:26:33.000
And of the nine I recall, I think, no, the Rock Hill team was what I used to call them.

00:26:33.000 --> 00:26:46.000
One of them withdrew from the demonstration aspects of that litigation because of his connection with one of the schools up there.

00:26:46.000 --> 00:26:56.000
And his fact that he was an athlete of some kind and was worried that he would lose his scholarship.

00:26:56.000 --> 00:27:14.000
Did you think of yourself then as being in your legal work for civil rights demonstrators most closely connected to your own private practice, to the state NAACP, to the legal defense fund effort?

00:27:14.000 --> 00:27:19.000
How did you think about your connections as a lawyer?

00:27:19.000 --> 00:27:28.000
You had to be as involved as you possibly could in all aspects of the community.

00:27:28.000 --> 00:27:42.000
In other words, if you're going to justify your existence as a lawyer, you had to be in a position to articulate the concerns of the various citizens that you would represent.

00:27:42.000 --> 00:27:55.000
I was most closely, I guess, identified with the NAACP because I knew the leadership and the better.

00:27:55.000 --> 00:28:04.000
I knew that the Sumpter NAACP was right there.

00:28:04.000 --> 00:28:12.000
And the Sumpter NAACP had a very active involvement in the total community.

00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:24.000
In fact, one of the things that attracted me to Sumpter was the fact that it had an active NAACP chapter.

00:28:24.000 --> 00:28:31.000
And they were on the forefront of the leadership of the civil rights movement.

00:28:31.000 --> 00:28:36.000
Excuse me, just one sec John Kelly Paws?

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:37.000
We're all working together.

00:28:37.000 --> 00:28:44.000
Okay, we're back. We took a break to try to adjust some outdoor heavy equipment folks were doing some work outside.

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:52.000
Just to spend the only, you had just talked a little bit about Dunder Connection with the state NAACP and the Sumpter chapter.

00:28:52.000 --> 00:29:01.000
Can you talk a little bit more describe the volume of your work on behalf of civil rights protesters in the early 60s because you were quite busy.

00:29:01.000 --> 00:29:17.000
Well, if you were going to be a lawyer and if you articulate the concerns of the Black community, you had to be everywhere at every time involved.

00:29:18.000 --> 00:29:30.000
And we were a cadre of good lawyers, interestingly enough, most of whom graduated from South Carolina State's law school.

00:29:30.000 --> 00:29:42.000
But they were hellbent bound in the term to make the American dream a reality in our lifetime.

00:29:42.000 --> 00:29:49.000
We didn't succeed in all of that. But of course, we diligently tried.

00:29:49.000 --> 00:30:11.000
And every time Matthew and I used to talk about the fact that, I don't know if we talked about it or it's reminisced about it, we would say that if a Greyhound bus had a major wreck in front of our enemy,

00:30:11.000 --> 00:30:19.000
our individual officers, we would not get the cases more than likely.

00:30:19.000 --> 00:30:31.000
That they would end up being become a client of one of the more established law firms.

00:30:31.000 --> 00:30:54.000
And we had to continually work to take the cases that were not significant financially in order to make a living and to serve our client there.

00:30:54.000 --> 00:31:02.000
Exactly. In 1963, you joined the South Carolina Human Rights Commission.

00:31:02.000 --> 00:31:21.000
Well, it was another avenue of opportunity for exposure and to connect yourself with a segment of the population that was not, you must remember,

00:31:21.000 --> 00:31:33.000
that in the days we were talking about the headquarters of the White Citizens Council was subterged.

00:31:33.000 --> 00:31:46.000
And at the same time, as I recall it, some of the White community was very active in the Human Rights Commission.

00:31:46.000 --> 00:31:52.000
I remember Mr. Dabs was very active.

00:31:52.000 --> 00:32:08.000
So you would affiliate yourself with everybody who might offer you an opportunity to become involved in the struggle for civil rights.

00:32:08.000 --> 00:32:21.000
And you know, I told you earlier about the number of schools I went through as a student.

00:32:21.000 --> 00:32:31.000
And I want you to know that I ran for political office three times.

00:32:31.000 --> 00:32:41.000
I got beat three times, but I never lost faith in the system. So finally I won.

00:32:41.000 --> 00:32:51.000
Indeed, in 1972, you'll win a seat on the state House of Representatives. But before I get to that, I want to ask out.

00:32:51.000 --> 00:33:00.000
I'm very interested in two things. One, your perspective on evolving race relations in South Carolina through the 60s.

00:33:00.000 --> 00:33:08.000
Voting Rights Act obviously gets passed. There's some early, some black candidates stand for election obviously in various races.

00:33:08.000 --> 00:33:14.000
And then you will be a delegate, you are a delegate to the Democratic National Convention in the year 1968.

00:33:14.000 --> 00:33:19.000
Those are two separate questions, but I'm interested in your perspective.

00:33:19.000 --> 00:33:28.000
What was your sense of the nature of evolving race relations in South Carolina through the 60s?

00:33:28.000 --> 00:33:34.000
We were disappointed that we did not make more progress.

00:33:34.000 --> 00:33:52.000
And particularly, what we disappointed in the fact that much of the progress we apparently were making did not benefit the most needy of the black community.

00:33:52.000 --> 00:34:06.000
And that's not an ancient story we're talking about. That's a current scenario that is still an issue.

00:34:06.000 --> 00:34:18.000
We have, I think, I'm probably sighted at a couple of times. You come out of Spottenberg and you look at the schools in Spottenberg County.

00:34:18.000 --> 00:34:36.000
And you come down to some of the less fortunate counties and you look at the conditions of our schools and everybody is talking about the card of shame and versus and sundry other aspects of our development.

00:34:36.000 --> 00:35:05.000
But we still need to spend more time, more energy on developing a school system that provides an opportunity for our children in particular the less fortunate communities to get the quality of education which will prepare them for living in the next century.

00:35:05.000 --> 00:35:20.000
In 1968, obviously early 1968, there's the horrible all the shootings at Orange and Orange Berk, the so-called Orange Berk Massacre.

00:35:20.000 --> 00:35:35.000
And a year later, watching the federal government's reaction to that, and it's the next administration's refusal to open a re-investigation.

00:35:35.000 --> 00:35:47.000
Not only did I resign, but a man by the name of Ben Peyton resigned. I think it proved Ben. And several other people.

00:35:47.000 --> 00:36:02.000
Because we felt that the federal government was not using all of its powers to see what the situation was and to investigate.

00:36:02.000 --> 00:36:22.000
And I was chairman of the Civil Rights Commission at that time, I believe. And of course, there was always the struggle between the people who were in power and the people who were representing the denied people.

00:36:22.000 --> 00:36:33.000
Not everybody. One side wanted everything done right then, and the other side wanted to say, let's wait and see.

00:36:33.000 --> 00:36:39.000
How did you put your race together in 1972 for the State House of Representatives?

00:36:39.000 --> 00:36:57.000
Oh, my gosh, how did I put it together? I was doing the same thing I've been doing for Get Out of the Street and talk to anybody, John, whoever would welcome me into a meeting.

00:36:57.000 --> 00:36:59.000
And try.

00:36:59.000 --> 00:37:02.000
Did it take a lot of money to run a race back then?

00:37:02.000 --> 00:37:12.000
If it did, I wouldn't have been in it. I can't afford it. But the people who were something were good to me.

00:37:12.000 --> 00:37:30.000
I had very few incidents where the underground of racial problems impacted my career, even the lawsuits I was involved in.

00:37:30.000 --> 00:37:44.000
I remember the journalist Jack Bass. He interviewed you in 1975 as he was doing a series of interviews across the South about changing Southern politics.

00:37:44.000 --> 00:37:57.000
And you talked in that interview about having pulled in your election, not insignificant portion of the White Book, maybe 20, 25% of the White Book.

00:37:57.000 --> 00:38:02.000
That's all I needed. After losing three times, I...

00:38:02.000 --> 00:38:07.000
We're going to put you on the back porch.

00:38:07.000 --> 00:38:09.000
Yeah, you go out there with Rusty.

00:38:09.000 --> 00:38:17.000
Mrs. Penny is trying just to spend, perhaps, female modest in this interview. I can tell myself that's a little bit true.

00:38:17.000 --> 00:38:19.000
More little bit true.

00:38:19.000 --> 00:38:23.000
You helped found the legislative Black Caucus immediately entering the state house.

00:38:23.000 --> 00:38:24.000
Yes.

00:38:24.000 --> 00:38:39.000
Because upon being elected to the State House, I felt that if the caucus was going to be effective, the first thing we had to do was to learn the rules.

00:38:40.000 --> 00:38:48.000
And in order to be a mechanism for good and change, you had to do that.

00:38:48.000 --> 00:38:59.000
The only way I could think of to do that was to have a caucus where you meet and study what the rules are and be prepared to meet the rules here.

00:38:59.000 --> 00:39:10.000
You know, that was why I was active with the other people who were in the caucus and formulating it.

00:39:10.000 --> 00:39:19.000
You know, there's no need of us being at the shouting and carrying on if we don't know the rules.

00:39:19.000 --> 00:39:32.000
Excuse me. How did you evaluate your years in the state legislature? Did you have your relationship with other folks who had the influence legislation?

00:39:32.000 --> 00:39:36.000
Oh, yes. We became a force.

00:39:36.000 --> 00:39:41.000
We were, there were three of us when I first got there, I think.

00:39:41.000 --> 00:39:49.000
But we were a force to be considered when the agenda was being adopted or approved.

00:39:49.000 --> 00:39:52.000
They got a little agentified going on over there now.

00:39:52.000 --> 00:39:57.000
Believe it. They ended up in the Supreme Court this week.

00:39:57.000 --> 00:40:01.000
Yes, they did.

00:40:01.000 --> 00:40:13.000
Let me ask you now about, about 1985 and your election to the State Supreme Court.

00:40:13.000 --> 00:40:18.000
A miracle still happened. You got to believe it.

00:40:18.000 --> 00:40:31.000
I ran because some of my friends said we never had anybody who had in recent times.

00:40:31.000 --> 00:40:37.000
And I thought I could win. And I ran and I won.

00:40:37.000 --> 00:40:42.000
It was an interesting challenge and rewarding career.

00:40:42.000 --> 00:40:49.000
Tell me about that campaign. What was involved in campaign for the Supreme Court in 1985?

00:40:49.000 --> 00:41:03.000
Well, I had an inside track because the South Carolina House of Representatives had 170, four members I believe, something like that.

00:41:03.000 --> 00:41:13.000
The Senate had 46. And so I naturally had an opportunity to work on the House.

00:41:13.000 --> 00:41:18.000
And the opposition was a senator. He worked on the Senate.

00:41:18.000 --> 00:41:32.000
And despite the fact that he had been a legislator for more years than I had, that I had a larger number of people who were intimately working with me on a daily basis.

00:41:32.000 --> 00:41:37.000
And that helped me.

00:41:37.000 --> 00:41:44.000
In 1994, of course, there would be chose as elected as Chief Justice.

00:41:44.000 --> 00:41:49.000
Yes. Can you recall that moment in your reaction?

00:41:49.000 --> 00:42:01.000
Well, you know, I am a firm believer that if you provide people an opportunity and you do your homework

00:42:01.000 --> 00:42:08.000
how can I say it? You will get a son vote.

00:42:08.000 --> 00:42:14.000
And the people of the legislature elected me as Chief Justice.

00:42:14.000 --> 00:42:28.000
I was shocked, pleased. But I have always believed that if you work hard, you will get your share of the vote.

00:42:28.000 --> 00:42:40.000
You never did hear, ask me about my most famous race that I lost. Who was it that I ran for the South Carolina?

00:42:40.000 --> 00:42:43.000
What did I run for?

00:42:43.000 --> 00:42:46.000
Friends, do you remember what I ran for?

00:42:46.000 --> 00:42:56.000
I got trounced. I ran for Congress. I forgot in the year. I forgot who it was.

00:42:56.000 --> 00:43:07.000
I ran against the current Congressmen, I believe. Right in campaign.

00:43:07.000 --> 00:43:14.000
So I was just wild about politics.

00:43:14.000 --> 00:43:17.000
What did you do when you were in the United States?

00:43:17.000 --> 00:43:20.000
That's right.

00:43:20.000 --> 00:43:26.000
I had forgotten about my most famous run.

00:43:26.000 --> 00:43:28.000
Was it Albert Watson?

00:43:28.000 --> 00:43:30.000
I don't recall actually.

00:43:30.000 --> 00:43:35.000
I think it was Albert Watson. I'm not sure.

00:43:35.000 --> 00:43:44.000
But I know that it was an open seat. I was a legitimate citizen. I could run. I ran.

00:43:44.000 --> 00:43:49.000
Probably got 1,800 votes, but I did by the means.

00:43:49.000 --> 00:43:53.000
So, like I was just sitting here, I used to be a journalist.

00:43:53.000 --> 00:43:54.000
Huh?

00:43:54.000 --> 00:43:56.000
Rob Chander?

00:43:56.000 --> 00:44:02.000
Oh, well, you know, that was, that was, they were trying to hustle me out of South Carolina.

00:44:02.000 --> 00:44:09.000
Probably, I was offered a job in the Justice Department.

00:44:09.000 --> 00:44:11.000
By Robert Kennedy, then?

00:44:11.000 --> 00:44:12.000
Yes.

00:44:12.000 --> 00:44:13.000
But.

00:44:13.000 --> 00:44:14.000
At least tell that story, yeah?

00:44:14.000 --> 00:44:21.000
Well, you know, when you get back, that was a food gracious day. How many years ago was that?

00:44:21.000 --> 00:44:31.000
All I remember is I received overtures from the Kennedy administration that because of something they had heard in their room.

00:44:31.000 --> 00:44:39.000
I remember that I could come to Washington and become affiliated with the Justice Department.

00:44:39.000 --> 00:44:42.000
Well, I was enjoying myself where I was.

00:44:42.000 --> 00:44:51.000
I was a member of the legislature. I was involved in my community. And that was where I wanted to be.

00:44:52.000 --> 00:45:00.000
And I was not. I didn't know what Washington. I knew what Washington would like because I'd go into high school in Washington.

00:45:00.000 --> 00:45:09.000
But I thought that South Carolina had been good to me and as long as they were good to me, I was going to stay here and work at it.

00:45:09.000 --> 00:45:18.000
Let me ask you one final big question. It's about education because you've obviously been quite an advocate for education for a long time.

00:45:18.000 --> 00:45:24.000
And as Chief Justice, you wrote in a case where you...

00:45:24.000 --> 00:45:27.000
Abigail versus the State of South Carolina. Good.

00:45:27.000 --> 00:45:28.000
Yes, sir.

00:45:28.000 --> 00:45:29.000
Tell me about it.

00:45:29.000 --> 00:45:32.000
No, please, would you tell me about it? And us about it.

00:45:32.000 --> 00:45:34.000
Well, let me tell you what.

00:45:34.000 --> 00:45:36.000
Go back after short break.

00:45:36.000 --> 00:45:38.000
Okay. Just a minute. We're talking about Abigail.

00:45:38.000 --> 00:46:00.000
Abigail was a novel and involved litigation where some of the school districts in the State of South Carolina sought additional support financially.

00:46:00.000 --> 00:46:09.000
And at the status of the case when it reached the Supreme Court, we were...

00:46:09.000 --> 00:46:20.000
Those of us who felt as I do it, that we had to do something to number one, keep the case alive.

00:46:20.000 --> 00:46:27.000
We didn't want it to end up being decided and going back and starting all over again.

00:46:27.000 --> 00:46:42.000
Then I think I probably was enthusiastic that if the case was kept alive, the legislature's leaders would have resolved the difference.

00:46:42.000 --> 00:47:03.000
The dilemma was that the legislative leaders by large were from large counties or from counties that had some basic support of education.

00:47:03.000 --> 00:47:12.000
They had the tax base. And the smaller counties had the lesser tax base.

00:47:12.000 --> 00:47:32.000
And so you were trying to walk a line where you keep the state involved in providing education and not give them something out that would have prohibited or stopped the state from supporting education.

00:47:32.000 --> 00:47:45.000
And so I probably said the thing that I have caught the most flack about in my lifetime was providing...

00:47:45.000 --> 00:47:51.000
It was almost as bad as separate but equal.

00:47:51.000 --> 00:47:57.000
And they are still fighting that battle. They have not resolved that battle.

00:47:57.000 --> 00:48:18.000
There is no way... It's going to be difficult to get the counties that have the tax base to share with the counties that don't have the tax base.

00:48:18.000 --> 00:48:32.000
No, how they go justified to their constituents supporting those constituents that they don't represent.

00:48:32.000 --> 00:48:39.000
That's the dilemma with which we will confirm it with.

00:48:39.000 --> 00:48:46.000
I wanted to, even after you left the bench in 2000, you have worked...

00:48:46.000 --> 00:48:54.000
You've done work, for example, with Governor Riley on efforts to kind of push back against voucher proposals.

00:48:54.000 --> 00:49:02.000
And I'm thinking all the way back to say the most brown litigation and the question of tuition grants and how...

00:49:02.000 --> 00:49:07.000
I wonder if you see a connection between that theme over all those degrees?

00:49:07.000 --> 00:49:12.000
Well, I think what I see most is the fact that somehow another...

00:49:12.000 --> 00:49:25.000
South Carolina is going to reach its potential and provide its citizens the kind of public education they need.

00:49:25.000 --> 00:49:38.000
We have got to get to the point where public education becomes a crying need, a desirable result.

00:49:38.000 --> 00:49:43.000
We haven't reached that yet.

00:49:43.000 --> 00:49:55.000
We've got the latest controversy from Down in Charleston.

00:49:55.000 --> 00:50:01.000
The company that is Amazon.

00:50:01.000 --> 00:50:13.000
We've got to find a way that everybody in South Carolina has got to want to help public education.

00:50:13.000 --> 00:50:24.000
I could make some comments about what we pay some of our public officials, but I think that would be inappropriate.

00:50:24.000 --> 00:50:26.000
Any final thoughts, Justice Smith?

00:50:26.000 --> 00:50:37.000
Well, I'm delighted. I'm having a nice time. My children are doing well and that people have been extraordinarily kind to me.

00:50:37.000 --> 00:50:55.000
And I think probably the most difficult decisions I made were the fact that in my years in the legislature, I was unauticaly opposed to the deaf penalty.

00:50:55.000 --> 00:51:16.000
And as my career has gone ahead, I have had to sentence a human being to die. That was the most difficult of the inner struggles that I had.

00:51:16.000 --> 00:51:37.000
My young man had robbed his grandmother and he had come into South Carolina and robbed a coindella and then raped one or two women.

00:51:37.000 --> 00:51:47.000
And of course, in my new job as a circuit judge, I was assigned to try.

00:51:47.000 --> 00:51:56.000
And the women he had raped, one of them lived, one died.

00:51:56.000 --> 00:52:16.000
And that one who lived testified against it. In Ory County, jury determined that the appropriate sanction should be death by electrocution.

00:52:16.000 --> 00:52:27.000
Now you're talking about hard, that was a hard day's work, but I had taken this oath tonight.

00:52:27.000 --> 00:52:41.000
Yeah. Well, just spending a lot of money, I want to thank you so much for spending your morning with us and welcoming us to your home. It's a great privilege and honor for us and you thank me for sharing this memory.

00:52:41.000 --> 00:52:54.000
Okay, you tell me what you want in the morning. I'll tell you what I can tell you. Thank you very much. I appreciate very much. Did I behave myself sufficiently?

00:52:54.000 --> 00:53:04.000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

